    },
    {
      "id": "folmlK5SqQLvkPOSGQHnh",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 370.5197493375977,
      "y": 15423.091078057467,
      "width": 1166,
      "height": 775,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#e03131",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffc9c9",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b5F",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 584114721,
      "version": 2715,
      "versionNonce": 1284543343,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1770382024699,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "But when Bob and Alice live on different shard then problem starts, things become messy, Because\nthese updated can't happen in one atomic operation, so what happen if we do deduction of Bob but \ncrediting to Alice fails, we end up in inconsistent state which is bad.\nSo the textbook solution that we heared is something called two phase commit oftentime denoted \nas 2PC like that,\nbasically there is a central cordinator, and that central coordinator first asks all shard, hey \nare you guys ready to this transaction then it waits for everyone to say yes before telling them\nall okay now its time we can commit, this ensures the consistency and it sounds great in theory.\n\nIn practice 2PC actually pretty slow, because if any shard or coordinator goes down in the middle\nof it, then the whole thing gets stuck and we end up in this lock which is super tough to get\nout of, thats why most production system actually try to avoid 2PC to some extent, so what we can \ndo instead\n\nOption 1 -> Try to avoid cross charge transaction, in our System design interview to the extent that\nwe can if we have a transaction try to make sure all of that data is on the single database. that\nshould be our golden rule to follow, Now its not always achievable, as is evidence here with our\nexample Alice and Bob exist on diff shards, there is no way that we can guarantee that the two\npeople who are involved in our bank transaction exists on the same shard, and so another option\n\nOption 2 -> Saga Pattern -> This works basically using a sequence of smaller operations, Each action\nhas whats called a compensating action that can be run in case things fail, So we are not going to \nit too much\nBut the basics is this step 1 deduct 5 from Bob on shard 3, step 2 add 5 to Alice on shard 1 if step 2\nfails, we dont magically roll everything back, instead we run what is that compensating action for step 2,\nwhihc is that we are going to refund Bob his 5 $. So its manual but ensures that we dont end up in a\nbroken state because it says each action we take has a opposite compensating reaction,such that if\nanything fails, we will run that compensating action in order to get back to the state that we want \nto be in.\nIts such that instead of one big transaction, we chain smaller steps together each of which has corres\nponding undo action associated.",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "But when Bob and Alice live on different shard then problem starts, things become messy, Because\nthese updated can't happen in one atomic operation, so what happen if we do deduction of Bob but \ncrediting to Alice fails, we end up in inconsistent state which is bad.\nSo the textbook solution that we heared is something called two phase commit oftentime denoted \nas 2PC like that,\nbasically there is a central cordinator, and that central coordinator first asks all shard, hey \nare you guys ready to this transaction then it waits for everyone to say yes before telling them\nall okay now its time we can commit, this ensures the consistency and it sounds great in theory.\n\nIn practice 2PC actually pretty slow, because if any shard or coordinator goes down in the middle\nof it, then the whole thing gets stuck and we end up in this lock which is super tough to get\nout of, thats why most production system actually try to avoid 2PC to some extent, so what we can \ndo instead\n\nOption 1 -> Try to avoid cross charge transaction, in our System design interview to the extent that\nwe can if we have a transaction try to make sure all of that data is on the single database. that\nshould be our golden rule to follow, Now its not always achievable, as is evidence here with our\nexample Alice and Bob exist on diff shards, there is no way that we can guarantee that the two\npeople who are involved in our bank transaction exists on the same shard, and so another option\n\nOption 2 -> Saga Pattern -> This works basically using a sequence of smaller operations, Each action\nhas whats called a compensating action that can be run in case things fail, So we are not going to \nit too much\nBut the basics is this step 1 deduct 5 from Bob on shard 3, step 2 add 5 to Alice on shard 1 if step 2\nfails, we dont magically roll everything back, instead we run what is that compensating action for step 2,\nwhihc is that we are going to refund Bob his 5 $. So its manual but ensures that we dont end up in a\nbroken state because it says each action we take has a opposite compensating reaction,such that if\nanything fails, we will run that compensating action in order to get back to the state that we want \nto be in.\nIts such that instead of one big transaction, we chain smaller steps together each of which has corres\nponding undo action associated.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
